<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!--
  Chapter 9 — Truth Tables

  Draft status:
  - First full draft: sections, chapter summary, key terms, and
    end-of-chapter exercises.
  - Introduces connectives as truth functions, well-formed formulas,
    order of operations, full truth tables, statement classification,
    pair relations, and argument validity.
  - Aligned with truthtablechecker/ V1.
-->
<chapter xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude" xml:id="ch-truth-tables">

  <title>Truth Tables</title>

  <introduction xml:id="ch-truth-tables-intro">
    <p>
      Chapter 8 taught the symbolic language of sentential logic.
      This chapter gives that language a method of evaluation. The
      method is the truth table. Truth tables let us determine the
      truth value of a compound statement from the truth values of
      its parts.
    </p>
    <p>
      The key idea is simple: the operators of sentential logic
      are <term>truth functions</term>. But, don't be scared. A function is just something that takes something and does something to it. A truth function takes truth
      values as inputs and returns a truth value as output. Since
      the only truth values in this system are T and F, these are
      among the simplest functions we can study.
    </p>
  </introduction>

  <section xml:id="sec-truth-functions">
    <title>Connectives as Truth Functions</title>

    <introduction>
      <p>
        A truth table is just a compact way of showing a function.
        The inputs go on the left. The output goes on the right.
      </p>
    </introduction>

    <definition xml:id="def-ch9-truth-table">
      <statement>
        <p>
          A <term>truth table</term> is a table that lists possible
          truth-value assignments and shows the truth value of a
          compound statement under each assignment.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>

    <definition xml:id="def-ch9-truth-function">
      <statement>
        <p>
          A <term>truth function</term> is a function whose inputs and
          output are truth values.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-truth-values-as-inputs">
      <title>Truth values as inputs</title>
      <p>
        In sentential logic, every statement is either true or
        false. Recall, that's how we've set up the whole system in
        this course, going back to <xref ref="def-statement"/>. We
        write those truth values as T and F. A simple statement such
        as <m>P</m> can have either value:
      </p>
      <table xml:id="table-single-statement-values">
        <title>Possible Truth Values for One Statement</title>
        <tabular halign="center">
          <row header="yes">
            <cell><m>P</m></cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell>T</cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell>F</cell>
          </row>
        </tabular>
      </table>
      <p>
        If an operator takes one statement as input, there are two
        possible input rows. Negation is like that. If a connective
        takes two statements as input, there are four possible input
        rows: TT, TF, FT, and FF. Conjunction, disjunction,
        conditional, and biconditional are like that.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-connectives-defined-by-output">
      <title>Connectives are defined by their outputs</title>
      <p>
        A connective is defined by what output it gives for each
        possible input. The horseshoe, for example, is the
        truth function that gives T for the TT, FT, and FF rows,
        and gives F for the TF row. Presented as a truth table:
      </p>
      <table xml:id="table-conditional-as-function">
        <title>The Conditional as a Truth Function</title>
        <tabular halign="center">
          <row header="yes">
            <cell><m>P</m></cell>
            <cell right="medium"><m>Q</m></cell>
            <cell><m>P</m></cell>
            <cell><m>\supset</m></cell>
            <cell><m>Q</m></cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell>T</cell>
            <cell right="medium">T</cell>
            <cell><m>{}</m></cell>
            <cell>T</cell>
            <cell><m>{}</m></cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell>T</cell>
            <cell right="medium">F</cell>
            <cell><m>{}</m></cell>
            <cell>F</cell>
            <cell><m>{}</m></cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell>F</cell>
            <cell right="medium">T</cell>
            <cell><m>{}</m></cell>
            <cell>T</cell>
            <cell><m>{}</m></cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell>F</cell>
            <cell right="medium">F</cell>
            <cell><m>{}</m></cell>
            <cell>T</cell>
            <cell><m>{}</m></cell>
          </row>
        </tabular>
      </table>
      <p>
        That table is not a shortcut for the definition. It is the
        definition. In this system, the conditional just is the
        function displayed by that table.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-truth-functional-limits">
      <title>What truth functions ignore</title>
      <p>
        Truth functions care only about truth values. They do not
        care about topic, tone, causation, timing, explanation, or
        whether the two statements have anything to do with each
        other. That can feel strange, especially for conditionals.
      </p>
      <p>
        <q>If the library closes early, then the train station is
        downtown</q> is odd English. But sentential logic asks only
        whether the antecedent is true and whether the consequent
        is true. The truth value of the whole conditional is then
        fixed by the conditional truth table.
      </p>
      <p>
        This is a deliberate simplification. Sentential logic does
        not capture every feature of ordinary language. It captures
        one feature cleanly: how the truth value of a compound
        statement depends on the truth values of its parts.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

  </section>

  <section xml:id="sec-basic-truth-tables">
    <title>The Basic Truth Tables</title>

    <introduction>
      <p>
        The five connectives are defined by five basic truth
        tables. Learn these tables before trying to build longer
        ones.
      </p>
    </introduction>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-negation-truth-table">
      <title>Negation</title>
      <p>
        Negation reverses the truth value of the statement it
        governs. If <m>P</m> is true, <m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}P</m>
        is false. If <m>P</m> is false,
        <m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}P</m> is true.
      </p>
      <table xml:id="table-negation">
        <title>Negation</title>
        <tabular halign="center">
          <row header="yes">
            <cell right="medium"><m>P</m></cell>
            <cell><m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}</m></cell>
            <cell><m>P</m></cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell right="medium">T</cell>
            <cell>F</cell>
            <cell><m>{}</m></cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell right="medium">F</cell>
            <cell>T</cell>
            <cell><m>{}</m></cell>
          </row>
        </tabular>
      </table>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-binary-truth-tables">
      <title>The four two-input connectives</title>
      <p>
        The remaining connectives take two statements as inputs.
        The reference columns always appear in the same order:
      </p>
      <table xml:id="table-two-statement-reference">
        <title>Reference Rows for Two Statements</title>
        <tabular halign="center">
          <row header="yes">
            <cell><m>P</m></cell>
            <cell><m>Q</m></cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell>T</cell>
            <cell>T</cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell>T</cell>
            <cell>F</cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell>F</cell>
            <cell>T</cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell>F</cell>
            <cell>F</cell>
          </row>
        </tabular>
      </table>
      <p>
        Conjunction is true only on the TT row. Disjunction is
        false only on the FF row. The conditional is false only on
        the TF row. The biconditional is true when the two inputs
        match.
      </p>
      <table xml:id="table-basic-binary-connectives">
        <title>Basic Truth Tables for Binary Connectives</title>
        <tabular halign="center">
          <row header="yes">
            <cell><m>P</m></cell>
            <cell right="medium"><m>Q</m></cell>
            <cell><m>P</m></cell>
            <cell><m>\cdot</m></cell>
            <cell><m>Q</m></cell>
            <cell><m>P</m></cell>
            <cell><m>\lor</m></cell>
            <cell><m>Q</m></cell>
            <cell><m>P</m></cell>
            <cell><m>\supset</m></cell>
            <cell><m>Q</m></cell>
            <cell><m>P</m></cell>
            <cell><m>\equiv</m></cell>
            <cell><m>Q</m></cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell>T</cell>
            <cell right="medium">T</cell>
            <cell><m>{}</m></cell>
            <cell>T</cell>
            <cell><m>{}</m></cell>
            <cell><m>{}</m></cell>
            <cell>T</cell>
            <cell><m>{}</m></cell>
            <cell><m>{}</m></cell>
            <cell>T</cell>
            <cell><m>{}</m></cell>
            <cell><m>{}</m></cell>
            <cell>T</cell>
            <cell><m>{}</m></cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell>T</cell>
            <cell right="medium">F</cell>
            <cell><m>{}</m></cell>
            <cell>F</cell>
            <cell><m>{}</m></cell>
            <cell><m>{}</m></cell>
            <cell>T</cell>
            <cell><m>{}</m></cell>
            <cell><m>{}</m></cell>
            <cell>F</cell>
            <cell><m>{}</m></cell>
            <cell><m>{}</m></cell>
            <cell>F</cell>
            <cell><m>{}</m></cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell>F</cell>
            <cell right="medium">T</cell>
            <cell><m>{}</m></cell>
            <cell>F</cell>
            <cell><m>{}</m></cell>
            <cell><m>{}</m></cell>
            <cell>T</cell>
            <cell><m>{}</m></cell>
            <cell><m>{}</m></cell>
            <cell>T</cell>
            <cell><m>{}</m></cell>
            <cell><m>{}</m></cell>
            <cell>F</cell>
            <cell><m>{}</m></cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell>F</cell>
            <cell right="medium">F</cell>
            <cell><m>{}</m></cell>
            <cell>F</cell>
            <cell><m>{}</m></cell>
            <cell><m>{}</m></cell>
            <cell>F</cell>
            <cell><m>{}</m></cell>
            <cell><m>{}</m></cell>
            <cell>T</cell>
            <cell><m>{}</m></cell>
            <cell><m>{}</m></cell>
            <cell>T</cell>
            <cell><m>{}</m></cell>
          </row>
        </tabular>
      </table>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-reading-basic-tables">
      <title>Reading a truth table</title>
      <p>
        Read across a row. The row tells you what the compound
        statement does under one possible assignment of truth
        values to its sentence letters.
      </p>
      <p>
        In the second row of the conditional table, <m>P</m> is T
        and <m>Q</m> is F. The output for <m>P \supset Q</m> is F.
        That row says: a conditional is false when its antecedent
        is true and its consequent is false.
      </p>
      <p>
        Every other row for the conditional is true. Again, that is
        not because of a story about causation or evidence. It is
        because the truth function for <m>\supset</m> is defined
        that way.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

  </section>

  <section xml:id="sec-well-formed-formulas">
    <title>Well-Formed Formulas and Order of Operations</title>

    <introduction>
      <p>
        Truth tables work only when the formula has a definite
        structure. Before we evaluate a formula, we need to know
        that it is well formed and know which parts to evaluate
        first.
      </p>
    </introduction>

    <definition xml:id="def-ch9-well-formed-formula">
      <statement>
        <p>
          A <term>well-formed formula</term> is a symbolic statement
          built according to the formation rules of the language.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-well-formed-formula">
      <title>Well-formed formulas</title>
      <p>
        A <term>well-formed formula</term> is a symbolic statement
        built according to the formation rules of the language. In
        this book, the rules are:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li><p>A capital sentence letter is a well-formed formula.</p></li>
        <li><p>If <m>P</m> is a well-formed formula, then <m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}P</m> is a well-formed formula.</p></li>
        <li><p>If <m>P</m> and <m>Q</m> are well-formed formulas, then <m>(P \cdot Q)</m>, <m>(P \lor Q)</m>, <m>(P \supset Q)</m>, and <m>(P \equiv Q)</m> are well-formed formulas.</p></li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        These rules are recursive: we can build larger formulas
        out of smaller formulas. <m>P</m> and <m>Q</m> are
        well-formed formulas. So <m>(P \cdot Q)</m> is a
        well-formed formula. Since <m>(P \cdot Q)</m> and
        <m>R</m> are well-formed formulas,
        <m>((P \cdot Q) \supset R)</m> is also a well-formed
        formula.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-outer-parentheses-convention">
      <title>Outer parentheses convention</title>
      <p>
        Strictly speaking, fully built formulas use parentheses
        around binary connectives. In ordinary practice, we often
        omit the outermost parentheses. So we write
        <m>P \cdot Q</m> rather than <m>(P \cdot Q)</m>, and
        <m>(P \cdot Q) \supset R</m> rather than
        <m>((P \cdot Q) \supset R)</m>.
      </p>
      <p>
        That convention is harmless because the omitted parentheses
        would wrap the whole formula. Internal parentheses are
        different. They often determine what the formula means.
      </p>
      <p>
        Compare:
      </p>
      <p><m>(P \cdot Q) \supset R</m></p>
      <p><m>P \cdot (Q \supset R)</m></p>
      <p>
        The first formula is a conditional. The second formula is a
        conjunction. Same letters, same connectives, different
        structure. Why? Because of the order of operations. 
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-order-of-operations">
      <title>Order of operations</title>
      <p>
        To build a truth table, evaluate the formula from the
        inside out:
      </p>
      <ol>
        <li><p>Fill the reference columns for the sentence letters.</p></li>
        <li><p>Evaluate innermost compounds first.</p></li>
        <li><p>Work outward one connective at a time.</p></li>
        <li><p>Finish with the main connective of the whole formula.</p></li>
      </ol>
      <definition xml:id="def-ch9-main-column">
        <statement>
          <p>
            The <term>main column</term> is the column of truth values
            under the main connective of the whole statement.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </definition>
      <p>
        For <m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}(P \cdot Q)</m>, the
        conjunction <m>P \cdot Q</m> must be evaluated before the
        negation of the whole conjunction. Put each truth value
        directly under the operator being evaluated: first under
        <m>\cdot</m>, then under <m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}</m>.
        The order row beneath the table records that sequence.
      </p>
      <table xml:id="table-negated-conjunction-order">
        <title>Order of Operations for a Negated Conjunction</title>
        <tabular halign="center">
          <row header="yes">
            <cell><m>P</m></cell>
            <cell right="medium"><m>Q</m></cell>
            <cell><m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}</m></cell>
            <cell><m>(</m></cell>
            <cell><m>P</m></cell>
            <cell><m>\cdot</m></cell>
            <cell><m>Q</m></cell>
            <cell><m>)</m></cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell>T</cell>
            <cell right="medium">T</cell>
            <cell>F</cell>
            <cell><m>{}</m></cell>
            <cell><m>{}</m></cell>
            <cell>T</cell>
            <cell><m>{}</m></cell>
            <cell><m>{}</m></cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell>T</cell>
            <cell right="medium">F</cell>
            <cell>T</cell>
            <cell><m>{}</m></cell>
            <cell><m>{}</m></cell>
            <cell>F</cell>
            <cell><m>{}</m></cell>
            <cell><m>{}</m></cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell>F</cell>
            <cell right="medium">T</cell>
            <cell>T</cell>
            <cell><m>{}</m></cell>
            <cell><m>{}</m></cell>
            <cell>F</cell>
            <cell><m>{}</m></cell>
            <cell><m>{}</m></cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell>F</cell>
            <cell right="medium">F</cell>
            <cell>T</cell>
            <cell><m>{}</m></cell>
            <cell><m>{}</m></cell>
            <cell>F</cell>
            <cell><m>{}</m></cell>
            <cell><m>{}</m></cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell><m>{}</m></cell>
            <cell right="medium"><m>{}</m></cell>
            <cell>2</cell>
            <cell><m>{}</m></cell>
            <cell><m>{}</m></cell>
            <cell>1</cell>
            <cell><m>{}</m></cell>
            <cell><m>{}</m></cell>
          </row>
        </tabular>
      </table>
      <p>
        The truth table checker follows this same order, but it
        expands the work into separate checkable columns so it can
        lock, grade, save, and describe each step accessibly.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

  </section>

  <section xml:id="sec-building-truth-tables">
    <title>Building Full Truth Tables</title>

    <introduction>
      <p>
        A full truth table considers every possible assignment of
        truth values to the sentence letters in a formula or
        argument.
      </p>
    </introduction>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-number-of-rows">
      <title>How many rows?</title>
      <p>
        The number of rows depends on the number of different
        sentence letters. One sentence letter gives two rows. Two
        sentence letters give four rows. Three sentence letters
        give eight rows. Four sentence letters give sixteen rows.
      </p>
      <p>
        The pattern is powers of two:
      </p>
      <table xml:id="table-truth-table-row-counts">
        <title>Rows in a Truth Table</title>
        <tabular halign="center">
          <row header="yes">
            <cell>Sentence letters</cell>
            <cell>Rows</cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell>1</cell>
            <cell>2</cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell>2</cell>
            <cell>4</cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell>3</cell>
            <cell>8</cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell>4</cell>
            <cell>16</cell>
          </row>
        </tabular>
      </table>
      <p>
        In this course, most tables stay at two or three sentence
        letters. Four-letter tables are possible, but they get wide
        quickly.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-reference-column-pattern">
      <title>The reference-column pattern</title>
      <p>
        Write the sentence letters in order of first appearance.
        Then fill the reference columns in a regular binary-counting
        pattern. The rightmost sentence-letter column alternates T,
        F, T, F. The next column changes every two rows. The next
        column changes every four rows.
      </p>
      <table xml:id="table-three-letter-reference-pattern">
        <title>Reference Columns for Three Sentence Letters</title>
        <tabular halign="center">
          <row header="yes">
            <cell><m>P</m></cell>
            <cell><m>Q</m></cell>
            <cell><m>R</m></cell>
          </row>
          <row><cell>T</cell><cell>T</cell><cell>T</cell></row>
          <row><cell>T</cell><cell>T</cell><cell>F</cell></row>
          <row><cell>T</cell><cell>F</cell><cell>T</cell></row>
          <row><cell>T</cell><cell>F</cell><cell>F</cell></row>
          <row><cell>F</cell><cell>T</cell><cell>T</cell></row>
          <row><cell>F</cell><cell>T</cell><cell>F</cell></row>
          <row><cell>F</cell><cell>F</cell><cell>T</cell></row>
          <row><cell>F</cell><cell>F</cell><cell>F</cell></row>
        </tabular>
      </table>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-worked-full-table">
      <title>A worked table</title>
      <p>
        Build the table for
        <m>(P \supset Q) \equiv ({\text{\textasciitilde}}P \lor Q)</m>.
        First evaluate the conditional <m>P \supset Q</m>. Then
        evaluate <m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}P</m>. Then evaluate
        <m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}P \lor Q</m>. Finally evaluate
        the biconditional joining the two larger parts. The truth
        values go under the operators that produce them.
      </p>
      <table xml:id="table-material-implication-worked">
        <title>A Complete Truth Table</title>
        <tabular halign="center">
          <row header="yes">
            <cell><m>P</m></cell>
            <cell right="medium"><m>Q</m></cell>
            <cell><m>(</m></cell>
            <cell><m>P</m></cell>
            <cell><m>\supset</m></cell>
            <cell><m>Q</m></cell>
            <cell><m>)</m></cell>
            <cell><m>\equiv</m></cell>
            <cell><m>(</m></cell>
            <cell><m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}</m></cell>
            <cell><m>P</m></cell>
            <cell><m>\lor</m></cell>
            <cell><m>Q</m></cell>
            <cell><m>)</m></cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell>T</cell>
            <cell right="medium">T</cell>
            <cell><m>{}</m></cell>
            <cell><m>{}</m></cell>
            <cell>T</cell>
            <cell><m>{}</m></cell>
            <cell><m>{}</m></cell>
            <cell>T</cell>
            <cell><m>{}</m></cell>
            <cell>F</cell>
            <cell><m>{}</m></cell>
            <cell>T</cell>
            <cell><m>{}</m></cell>
            <cell><m>{}</m></cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell>T</cell>
            <cell right="medium">F</cell>
            <cell><m>{}</m></cell>
            <cell><m>{}</m></cell>
            <cell>F</cell>
            <cell><m>{}</m></cell>
            <cell><m>{}</m></cell>
            <cell>T</cell>
            <cell><m>{}</m></cell>
            <cell>F</cell>
            <cell><m>{}</m></cell>
            <cell>F</cell>
            <cell><m>{}</m></cell>
            <cell><m>{}</m></cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell>F</cell>
            <cell right="medium">T</cell>
            <cell><m>{}</m></cell>
            <cell><m>{}</m></cell>
            <cell>T</cell>
            <cell><m>{}</m></cell>
            <cell><m>{}</m></cell>
            <cell>T</cell>
            <cell><m>{}</m></cell>
            <cell>T</cell>
            <cell><m>{}</m></cell>
            <cell>T</cell>
            <cell><m>{}</m></cell>
            <cell><m>{}</m></cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell>F</cell>
            <cell right="medium">F</cell>
            <cell><m>{}</m></cell>
            <cell><m>{}</m></cell>
            <cell>T</cell>
            <cell><m>{}</m></cell>
            <cell><m>{}</m></cell>
            <cell>T</cell>
            <cell><m>{}</m></cell>
            <cell>T</cell>
            <cell><m>{}</m></cell>
            <cell>T</cell>
            <cell><m>{}</m></cell>
            <cell><m>{}</m></cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell><m>{}</m></cell>
            <cell right="medium"><m>{}</m></cell>
            <cell><m>{}</m></cell>
            <cell><m>{}</m></cell>
            <cell>2</cell>
            <cell><m>{}</m></cell>
            <cell><m>{}</m></cell>
            <cell>4</cell>
            <cell><m>{}</m></cell>
            <cell>1</cell>
            <cell><m>{}</m></cell>
            <cell>3</cell>
            <cell><m>{}</m></cell>
            <cell><m>{}</m></cell>
          </row>
        </tabular>
      </table>
      <p>
        The main column is the column under <m>\equiv</m>. Because the two inputs into the triple bar, the results under horseshoe and the results under the wedge, all match, the triple bar outputs all T. The whole statement is true under every possible
        assignment of truth values to <m>P</m> and <m>Q</m>. This tells us that the statement is a tautology.      </p>
    </paragraphs>

  </section>

  <section xml:id="sec-using-truth-tables">
    <title>Using Truth Tables</title>

    <introduction>
      <p>
        Once a truth table is complete, the values under the main
        operator can answer three kinds of questions: What kind of
        statement is this? How do these two statements relate? Is
        this argument valid?
      </p>
    </introduction>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-statement-classification">
      <title>Classifying single statements</title>
      <p>
        A statement is a <term>tautology</term> if the values under
        its main operator are all T. It is a
        <term>self-contradiction</term> if the values under its main
        operator are all F. It is <term>contingent</term> if those
        values contain at least one T and at least one F.
      </p>
      <definition xml:id="def-ch9-tautology">
        <statement>
          <p>
            A <term>tautology</term> is a statement whose main
            truth-table column is all T.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </definition>
      <definition xml:id="def-ch9-self-contradiction">
        <statement>
          <p>
            A <term>self-contradiction</term> is a statement whose
            main truth-table column is all F.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </definition>
      <definition xml:id="def-ch9-contingent">
        <statement>
          <p>
            A <term>contingent</term> statement has a main
            truth-table column with at least one T and at least one F.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </definition>
      <table xml:id="table-statement-classification">
        <title>Classifying Statements</title>
        <tabular halign="center">
          <row header="yes">
            <cell>Values under main operator</cell>
            <cell>Classification</cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell>All T</cell>
            <cell>Tautology</cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell>All F</cell>
            <cell>Self-contradiction</cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell>At least one T and at least one F</cell>
            <cell>Contingent</cell>
          </row>
        </tabular>
      </table>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-pair-relations">
      <title>Comparing pairs of statements</title>
      <p>
        To compare two statements, compare the values under their
        main operators row by row.
      </p>
      <definition xml:id="def-ch9-logically-equivalent">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Two statements are <term>logically equivalent</term> when
            the values under their main operators match on every row.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </definition>
      <definition xml:id="def-ch9-contradictory">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Two statements are <term>contradictory</term> when their
            values under their main operators differ on every row.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </definition>
      <definition xml:id="def-ch9-consistent-not-equivalent">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Two statements are <term>consistent but not equivalent</term>
            when the values under their main operators share at least
            one T row, but do not match on every row.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </definition>
      <definition xml:id="def-ch9-inconsistent-not-contradictory">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Two statements are
            <term>inconsistent but not contradictory</term> when their
            values under their main operators never share a T row,
            but are not opposites on every row.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </definition>
      <p>
        These four labels match the truth table checker. The
        checker will not choose the relation for you; it will ask
        you to compare the main-operator values and choose the right
        relation.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-argument-validity-truth-tables">
      <title>Testing arguments</title>
      <p>
        A truth table tests an argument by looking for a
        counterexample row.
      </p>
      <definition xml:id="def-ch9-counterexample-row">
        <statement>
          <p>
            A <term>counterexample row</term> is a truth-table row
            where every premise is true and the conclusion is false.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </definition>
      <p>
        If there is no counterexample row, the argument is valid.
        If there is at least one counterexample row, the argument
        is invalid.
      </p>
      <example xml:id="ex-truth-table-invalid-argument">
        <title>An Invalid Argument</title>
        <statement>
          <p>P1: <m>P \supset Q</m></p>
          <p>P2: <m>Q</m></p>
          <p><m>\therefore</m> C: <m>P</m></p>
        </statement>
      </example>
      <table xml:id="table-invalid-argument-counterexample">
        <title>Testing for a Counterexample Row</title>
        <tabular halign="center">
          <row header="yes">
            <cell><m>P</m></cell>
            <cell right="medium"><m>Q</m></cell>
            <cell>P1:</cell>
            <cell><m>P</m></cell>
            <cell><m>\supset</m></cell>
            <cell><m>Q</m></cell>
            <cell right="medium">P2: <m>Q</m></cell>
            <cell>C: <m>P</m></cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell>T</cell>
            <cell right="medium">T</cell>
            <cell><m>{}</m></cell>
            <cell><m>{}</m></cell>
            <cell>T</cell>
            <cell><m>{}</m></cell>
            <cell>T</cell>
            <cell>T</cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell>T</cell>
            <cell right="medium">F</cell>
            <cell><m>{}</m></cell>
            <cell><m>{}</m></cell>
            <cell>F</cell>
            <cell><m>{}</m></cell>
            <cell>F</cell>
            <cell>T</cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell>F</cell>
            <cell right="medium">T</cell>
            <cell><m>{}</m></cell>
            <cell><m>{}</m></cell>
            <cell>T</cell>
            <cell><m>{}</m></cell>
            <cell>T</cell>
            <cell>F</cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell>F</cell>
            <cell right="medium">F</cell>
            <cell><m>{}</m></cell>
            <cell><m>{}</m></cell>
            <cell>T</cell>
            <cell><m>{}</m></cell>
            <cell>F</cell>
            <cell>F</cell>
          </row>
        </tabular>
      </table>
      <p>
        The third row is a counterexample row: both premises are
        true, but the conclusion is false. So the argument is
        invalid.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

  </section>

  <section xml:id="sec-truth-tables-where-headed">
    <title>Where We're Headed</title>

    <p>
      Truth tables are powerful because they are mechanical. If a
      symbolic statement has four or fewer sentence letters, you
      can test it by listing the possible truth-value assignments
      and calculating the values under the main operator. The method is slow by hand,
      but it is exact.
    </p>
    <p>
      The next chapter turns to natural deduction. Truth tables
      tell us whether an argument is valid. Natural deduction gives
      us a different kind of understanding: it shows how to move
      from premises to conclusion step by step using rules.
    </p>

  </section>

  <conclusion xml:id="conclusion-ch9">
    <title>Chapter Summary</title>

    <p>
      This chapter introduced truth tables as a method for
      evaluating sentential formulas and arguments.
    </p>
    <p>
      <alert>Connectives as Truth Functions (§9.1).</alert> A
      connective is defined by the output it gives for each
      possible input of truth values.
    </p>
    <p>
      <alert>The Basic Truth Tables (§9.2).</alert> Negation,
      conjunction, disjunction, conditional, and biconditional each
      have a defining truth table.
    </p>
    <p>
      <alert>Well-Formed Formulas and Order of Operations (§9.3).</alert>
      Truth tables require well-formed formulas. Work from the
      inside out and finish with the main connective.
    </p>
    <p>
      <alert>Building Full Truth Tables (§9.4).</alert> A full
      truth table lists every possible assignment of truth values
      to the sentence letters and then evaluates the compound
      formulas column by column.
    </p>
    <p>
      <alert>Using Truth Tables (§9.5).</alert> Truth tables
      classify single statements, compare pairs of statements, and
      test arguments for validity by looking for counterexample
      rows.
    </p>

  </conclusion>

  <section xml:id="sec-ch9-key-terms">
    <title>Key Terms</title>

    <p>Listed alphabetically, with section references.</p>

    <dl>
      <li xml:id="term-ch9-consistent-not-equivalent">
        <title>Consistent but not equivalent</title>
        <p>A relation between two statements whose main-operator values share at least one T row but do not match on every row. (§9.5)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-ch9-contingent">
        <title>Contingent</title>
        <p>A statement whose main truth-table column contains at least one T and at least one F. (§9.5)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-ch9-contradictory">
        <title>Contradictory</title>
        <p>A relation between two statements whose main-operator values differ on every row. (§9.5)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-ch9-counterexample-row">
        <title>Counterexample row</title>
        <p>A truth-table row where every premise is true and the conclusion is false. (§9.5)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-ch9-inconsistent-not-contradictory">
        <title>Inconsistent but not contradictory</title>
        <p>A relation between two statements whose main-operator values never share a T row but are not opposites on every row. (§9.5)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-ch9-logically-equivalent">
        <title>Logically equivalent</title>
        <p>A relation between two statements whose main-operator values match on every row. (§9.5)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-ch9-main-column">
        <title>Main column</title>
        <p>The column of truth values under the main connective of the whole statement. (§9.3, §9.4)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-ch9-self-contradiction">
        <title>Self-contradiction</title>
        <p>A statement whose main truth-table column is all F. (§9.5)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-ch9-tautology">
        <title>Tautology</title>
        <p>A statement whose main truth-table column is all T. (§9.5)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-ch9-truth-function">
        <title>Truth function</title>
        <p>A function whose inputs and output are truth values. (§9.1)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-ch9-truth-table">
        <title>Truth table</title>
        <p>A table that lists possible truth-value assignments and shows the truth value of a compound statement under each assignment. (§9.1)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-ch9-well-formed-formula">
        <title>Well-formed formula</title>
        <p>A symbolic statement built according to the formation rules of the language. (§9.3)</p>
      </li>
    </dl>

  </section>

  <exercises xml:id="exercises-ch9">
    <title>End-of-Chapter Exercises</title>

    <exercisegroup xml:id="exgroup-ch9-s01">
      <title>Exercise Set 1: Basic Truth Tables</title>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          For each formula, write the truth values under the main
          operator.
        </p>
      </introduction>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch9-s01-01"><statement><p><m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}P</m></p></statement></exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch9-s01-02"><statement><p><m>P \cdot Q</m></p></statement></exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch9-s01-03"><statement><p><m>P \lor Q</m></p></statement></exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch9-s01-04"><statement><p><m>P \supset Q</m></p></statement></exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch9-s01-05"><statement><p><m>P \equiv Q</m></p></statement></exercise>
    </exercisegroup>

    <exercisegroup xml:id="exgroup-ch9-s02">
      <title>Exercise Set 2: Well-Formed Formulas</title>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          For each expression, say whether it is well formed. If it
          is not, briefly explain the problem.
        </p>
      </introduction>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch9-s02-01"><statement><p><m>(P \cdot Q)</m></p></statement></exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch9-s02-02"><statement><p><m>P \supset (Q \lor R)</m></p></statement></exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch9-s02-03"><statement><p><m>P \cdot \lor Q</m></p></statement></exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch9-s02-04"><statement><p><m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}(P \equiv Q)</m></p></statement></exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch9-s02-05"><statement><p><m>(P \supset Q</m></p></statement></exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch9-s02-06"><statement><p><m>P Q \cdot R</m></p></statement></exercise>
    </exercisegroup>

    <exercisegroup xml:id="exgroup-ch9-s03">
      <title>Exercise Set 3: Order of Operations</title>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          For each formula, number the operators in the order they
          should be completed in a truth table.
        </p>
      </introduction>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch9-s03-01"><statement><p><m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}(P \cdot Q)</m></p></statement></exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch9-s03-02"><statement><p><m>P \supset (Q \cdot R)</m></p></statement></exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch9-s03-03"><statement><p><m>(P \lor Q) \cdot {\text{\textasciitilde}}R</m></p></statement></exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch9-s03-04"><statement><p><m>(P \supset Q) \equiv ({\text{\textasciitilde}}P \lor Q)</m></p></statement></exercise>
    </exercisegroup>

    <exercisegroup xml:id="exgroup-ch9-s04">
      <title>Exercise Set 4: Classifying Statements</title>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          Build a full truth table for each statement and classify
          it as a tautology, self-contradiction, or contingent.
        </p>
      </introduction>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch9-s04-01"><statement><p><m>P \lor {\text{\textasciitilde}}P</m></p></statement></exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch9-s04-02"><statement><p><m>P \cdot {\text{\textasciitilde}}P</m></p></statement></exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch9-s04-03"><statement><p><m>P \supset Q</m></p></statement></exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch9-s04-04"><statement><p><m>(P \cdot Q) \supset P</m></p></statement></exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch9-s04-05"><statement><p><m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}(P \lor Q)</m></p></statement></exercise>
    </exercisegroup>

    <exercisegroup xml:id="exgroup-ch9-s05">
      <title>Exercise Set 5: Comparing Pairs</title>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          Build truth tables and classify each pair as logically
          equivalent, contradictory, consistent but not equivalent,
          or inconsistent but not contradictory.
        </p>
      </introduction>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch9-s05-01"><statement><p><m>P \supset Q</m> and <m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}P \lor Q</m></p></statement></exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch9-s05-02"><statement><p><m>P \cdot Q</m> and <m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}(P \cdot Q)</m></p></statement></exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch9-s05-03"><statement><p><m>P</m> and <m>P \lor Q</m></p></statement></exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch9-s05-04"><statement><p><m>P \cdot Q</m> and <m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}P</m></p></statement></exercise>
    </exercisegroup>

    <exercisegroup xml:id="exgroup-ch9-s06">
      <title>Exercise Set 6: Testing Arguments</title>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          Use a truth table to determine whether each argument is
          valid. If it is invalid, identify a counterexample row.
        </p>
      </introduction>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch9-s06-01">
        <statement>
          <tabular halign="left" margins="0% 65%">
            <row><cell>P1:</cell><cell><m>P \supset Q</m></cell></row>
            <row><cell>P2:</cell><cell><m>P</m></cell></row>
            <row><cell><m>\therefore</m> C:</cell><cell><m>Q</m></cell></row>
          </tabular>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch9-s06-02">
        <statement>
          <tabular halign="left" margins="0% 65%">
            <row><cell>P1:</cell><cell><m>P \supset Q</m></cell></row>
            <row><cell>P2:</cell><cell><m>Q</m></cell></row>
            <row><cell><m>\therefore</m> C:</cell><cell><m>P</m></cell></row>
          </tabular>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch9-s06-03">
        <statement>
          <tabular halign="left" margins="0% 65%">
            <row><cell>P1:</cell><cell><m>P \lor Q</m></cell></row>
            <row><cell>P2:</cell><cell><m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}P</m></cell></row>
            <row><cell><m>\therefore</m> C:</cell><cell><m>Q</m></cell></row>
          </tabular>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch9-s06-04">
        <statement>
          <tabular halign="left" margins="0% 65%">
            <row><cell>P1:</cell><cell><m>P \supset Q</m></cell></row>
            <row><cell>P2:</cell><cell><m>Q \supset R</m></cell></row>
            <row><cell><m>\therefore</m> C:</cell><cell><m>P \supset R</m></cell></row>
          </tabular>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
    </exercisegroup>

  </exercises>

</chapter>
